The fixed fstab (clean + Plex-friendly)

I made you a corrected /etc/fstab that:

keeps your proc + PARTUUID boot/root lines

uses one consistent CIFS option set (uid=1000, gid=media, 0664/0775)

uses lowercase share names for the server drive letters (/d /e /f /i /j /m) since that’s what your working mounts showed

adds bind mounts under /mnt/plex so Plex only browses what you care about (no AppData/ProgramData clutter)

✅ Download it here: fstab.cleaned

What to do next (exact steps)
1) Make sure these directories exist
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/lan
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/lan/grab-{programdata,appdata,users,downloads,media,m,sidscri-apps,tempcomplete,asa-servers}
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/lan/server-{users,programdata,d,e,f,i,j,m,ebooks-and-audiobooks,portable-apps}

sudo mkdir -p /mnt/plex
sudo mkdir -p /mnt/plex/{grab-media,grab-m,server-d,server-e,server-f,server-i,server-j,server-m,server-users}

2) Ensure Plex + you share the media group
sudo groupadd -f media
sudo usermod -aG media plex
sudo usermod -aG media sidscri

3) Replace fstab

(Keep a backup first.)

sudo cp /etc/fstab /etc/fstab.backup.$(date +%F-%H%M)
sudo cp /mnt/data/fstab.cleaned /etc/fstab
sudo systemctl daemon-reload

4) Clear the “busy” old automount mounts (do this once)

This cleanly stops the automount units and unmounts old CIFS mounts:

# Stop all automount units under /mnt/lan and /mnt/plex
systemctl list-units --type=automount | awk '/mnt-lan|mnt-plex/{print $1}' | sudo xargs -r systemctl stop

# Unmount anything currently mounted under /mnt/lan or /mnt/plex
mount | awk '$3 ~ "^/mnt/(lan|plex)/" {print $3}' | sort -r | sudo xargs -r umount -f

5) Mount everything using the new fstab
sudo mount -a

6) Quick verification tests
# Trigger mounts
ls /mnt/lan/grab-media >/dev/null
ls /mnt/lan/server-d >/dev/null

# Check plex can read/write where it should
sudo -u plex bash -lc "touch /mnt/plex/grab-media/.plex_rw && rm -f /mnt/plex/grab-media/.plex_rw && echo plex_OK"

Plex setup (so the UI is not “confusing”)

When Plex asks you to browse folders for libraries, only browse under:

/mnt/plex/grab-media

/mnt/plex/grab-m

/mnt/plex/server-d (and the other server-* ones)

That way Plex won’t show AppData/ProgramData/etc while you’re picking folders.

One important callout about \040

That is correct in fstab. It’s just how spaces are encoded in mount entries (so “ASA Servers” becomes ASA\040Servers). The bind-mount /mnt/plex/... paths avoid you having to deal with that inside Plex browsing.

If you run sudo mount -a again and it still prints permission denied, paste just this (it’s short and tells us exactly which share is failing):

sudo journalctl -b --no-pager | tail -n 80